english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Poeun
  author: Kwon Chae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Writing carries the Way. Thus the Classics and the Records, the Rites and Music—their ceremonial forms and refined words—all embody the highest Way. In the age of the Three Dynasties and before, writing and the Way were one. After the Three Dynasties, writing and the Way became two. The three hundred poems of the *Classic of Poetry* are encompassed in a single principle: "thoughts free from depravity." The Master's compositions are nothing but the circulation of Heaven's principle. As it is said, "Those with virtue must have worthy words"—thus writing and the Way were initially without distinction.

    From the Han and Wei dynasties onward, those who gained renown through writing—Wang, Xu, Yuan, Liu, Cao, Bao, Shen, Xie, and descending through Tang and Song to Liu, Liu, Su, and Huang—each age produced its talents. Yet they merely excelled at depicting wind and cloud, moon and dew, fashioning images of things with practiced parallelism and hackneyed ornament. As for the Way, they scarcely had any understanding at all. Though their writings possessed certain merits, when one examines their conduct, all prove unworthy of serious regard. Thus it is that those with eloquent words need not possess virtue, and writing and the Way began to diverge into two separate things.

    Our Eastern lands have emulated the Rites and Music and cultural refinements of the Middle Kingdom. Scholars of letters have arisen in every age. Yet how many have combined talent and virtue both, whose names and substance mutually accord? Master Chong Mun-chung of Poeun, of Wuchon, emerged in the twilight of Koryo. Endowed with pure and radiant nature, possessed of profound and meticulous learning, his method of study made silent apprehension and heart-fusion paramount, with practice and personal conduct as the foundation. He established the study of principle and nature in the East, and the eminent worthies of his age all revered and followed him. Mok-un praised his lectures, saying: "Whether speaking crosswise or lengthwise, nothing fails to accord with principle." Do-un, in assessing his character, ever commended his exceptional virtue. Thus we may know his talent and learning.

    As to the traces of his deeds: when the Central Plains underwent revolution and our nation faced grave trials, he journeyed westward to pay court and eastward as emissary, avoiding no difficulty, caring for the realm and forgetting his household. His achievements were manifest, his benefits to our people well-known to all. When Koryo's fortune waned and Heaven brought forth one of sacred virtue, he alone bore upon his shoulders five hundred years of dynastic continuity, and ultimately fell before the white blade, preserving his great integrity. His solemn and unwavering loyalty contended with the radiant sun in brilliance. Truly, he was a minister of the realm, one whose fate intertwined with the nation's rise and fall. His coming into being had its cause; his departure had its purpose.

    Such was the Master's entire course—witness to the profundity of his attainment and the steadfastness of his conviction. Looking upward, he is guiltless before Heaven; looking downward, he stands unashamed before men. Because what dwelt within him was thus, his written words manifest themselves with robust depth and refined vigor, with mellow substance and harmonious calm. The devotion to his sovereign and loyalty to his realm overflow beyond the bounds of language itself. How profoundly does this touch upon human relationships and the instruction of the world! Can it be said to rest merely upon the refinement of diction and the craft of prosody? Truly, he possessed both virtue and worthy words, his name and substance accord as one, and writing and the Way were both complete in him.

    Our dynasty, having received the Mandate of Heaven, saw the great King Taejong prize his integrity and specially bestow upon him ennobling titles and honors, enrolling his descendants. Our Sovereign Lord commanded his portrait painted and an inscription composed to be placed among the memorials of the loyal. His son, Minister Chong-sung, compiled his surviving manuscripts and presented them. The command was given to me to write this preface to their pages. Such is the extent and perfection of the court's praise and honor. Through our dynasty, the Master's integrity has grown ever higher; through the Master, our sacred dynasty's virtue has grown ever greater. The establishment of the Way of hierarchy for all generations, the inspiration of the scholarly spirit—these hinges upon this. How then could this collection, transmitted to the world, be of little benefit?
  footnotes:
    - Poeun (1337-1392), given name Chong Mun-chung (鄭文忠), was a renowned Koryo statesman and Neo-Confucian scholar who maintained his integrity throughout the dynastic transition from Koryo to Choson, ultimately sacrificing his life rather than serve the new dynasty.
    - The references to "wind and cloud, moon and dew" allude to the aestheticism of medieval Chinese literature, which the author critiques as lacking moral grounding.
    - '"One of sacred virtue" refers to the founder of the Choson dynasty, whose legitimacy rested partly on Confucian virtue ethics.'
